            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Adrian Kaur\u2019s name is the first curiosity people notice, a Sikh surname paired with a distinctly white, European face. The story begins with his parents: a progressive, intellectual father from Ohio who, upon marrying a brilliant Punjabi engineer in the 1970s, took her name as a testament to their partnership. Raised in a quiet university town in Illinois, Adrian inherited his father's analytical mind and his mother's passion for how things are made. His childhood was spent disassembling appliances and building intricate Lego contraptions, a prelude to his future.\n\nHe pursued this passion with methodical focus, earning both a bachelor's and a master's degree in Mechanical Engineering from Purdue. The dot-com boom of the late '90s pulled him west, but unlike his peers chasing software fortunes, Adrian was drawn to the tangible world of hardware. He found his calling in the Bay Area's resurgent manufacturing sector, designing and optimizing the physical creation of technology.\n\nHis career was a steady, impressive climb. He started as a floor engineer, eventually becoming the Director of Manufacturing Engineering for a company producing high-end consumer electronics in the Dogpatch. The key turning point in his life wasn't professional, but personal: a divorce in his late thirties. Amicable but emotionally taxing, it coincided with a period of intense professional pressure, leaving him feeling isolated. He poured his energy into his work, his precision on the factory floor a calming contrast to his unstructured personal life.\n\nNow 48, Adrian\u2019s life is one of comfortable routine. He lives in a meticulously maintained flat in the Inner Richmond, appreciating the neighborhood's quiet and its proximity to Golden Gate Park. Each morning, he drives his Audi sedan the 7.5 miles to his office, a commute he uses to mentally prepare for a day of problem-solving. His social circle is small and loyal, comprised of old colleagues who share his love for engineering and deep conversation. He\u2019s financially secure but finds little joy in extravagance. His dream isn't a bigger title, but a slower life\u2014perhaps consulting part-time, allowing him to finally build the wooden kayak he\u2019s designed or take a long-overdue trip to India to connect with his mother\u2019s roots. He yearns to manufacture a life with more personal meaning, not just a more efficient product."
